data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** The syntax is straightforward:

```csharp
Span<nint>  nints  = stackalloc nint[5];
Span<nuint> nuints = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

This works in a safe context (no `unsafe` required) because the result is assigned to a `Span<T>`. On this 64-bit system, each `nint`/`nuint` is 8 bytes; on a 32-bit runtime they'd be 4 bytes. This has been supported since C# 9 / .NET 5 when `nint`/`nuint` were introduced as first-class types.
